# Real-Time Notification Mechanism

The application uses **WebSocket** for instant notification delivery.

## WebSocket Connection

```
wss://api.example.com/ws/notifications
```

### Connection Headers

```
Authorization: Bearer <JWT_TOKEN>
```

---

## Event: notification.created

Server sends:

```json
{
  "event": "notification.created",
  "data": {
    "id": "notif_205",
    "title": "New Course Available",
    "message": "A new course has been added.",
    "type": "info",
    "isRead": false,
    "createdAt": "2026-06-30T10:00:00Z"
  }
}
```

Frontend actions:

- Display notification popup
- Increase unread count
- Add notification to notification list

---

## Event: notification.updated

```json
{
  "event": "notification.updated",
  "data": {
    "id": "notif_205",
    "isRead": true
  }
}
```

---

## Event: notification.deleted

```json
{
  "event": "notification.deleted",
  "data": {
    "id": "notif_205"
  }
}
```

---

# API Summary

| Method | Endpoint | Description |
|----------|-----------------------------|---------------------------|
|GET|/notifications|Get all notifications|
|GET|/notifications/{id}|Get notification details|
|PATCH|/notifications/{id}/read|Mark notification as read|
|PATCH|/notifications/read-all|Mark all notifications as read|
|DELETE|/notifications/{id}|Delete notification|
|WebSocket|/ws/notifications|Receive live notifications|

---

# Design Highlights

- RESTful endpoint naming conventions
- JWT-based authentication
- Consistent JSON request and response formats
- Pagination support
- Standard HTTP status codes
- Uniform error handling
- Real-time updates via WebSockets
- Scalable and frontend-friendly API design
